%description:
TCP AccECN (Workstream G) G8.1: byte-exact CE feedback for DcTcp, superseding
RFC 8257's boolean gotEce-gated approximation. Client runs DcTcp,
tcpEcnMode="accecn", accEcnOptionEnabled=true, accEcnOptionBeaconAcks=1.
The client sends 5 MSS-sized segments in one burst; the tester marks only
the FIRST of them CE and drops the server's first 4 individual ACKs, so
the client sees a single cumulative ACK covering all 5 newly-acked
segments' bytes, with the AccECN option reporting the real ~1-segment CE
byte count.

A second, follow-up 100B send at t=1.0 forces one more ACK round after
the burst: G8's byte-exact accounting has a one-ACK lag by design (the
AccECN option/ACE for a given segment is decoded in
processAckInEstabEtc()'s ACE block, which runs AFTER
tcpAlgorithm->receivedDataAck() for that same segment -- see the code
comment), so the marked=988 assertion below is observed on the ACK for
this follow-up send, not on the burst-covering ACK itself (which, at
the time DcTcp checks it, still shows the OLD marks: ceBytesThisRound=0
cePktsThisRound=0 -- also asserted below, to pin the lag itself as
expected behavior rather than a flake).

The point of this scenario (deliberately "partial-segment CE marking
... out of several delivered in one round", per the plan): RFC 8257's
boolean approximation would mark this WHOLE round's bytes_acked (~5
segments, ~4940 bytes) since ECE/dctcp_ce would be true for the round,
while AccECN's byte-exact evidence correctly marks only the ~1
CE-marked segment's real payload (988 bytes -- reduced from the 1000B
MSS by the AccECN option's own 12-byte wire overhead on that segment).

Falsification: an identical scenario with accEcnOptionBeaconAcks=1000000
(never actually beacons within this test's short duration, starving the
option path exactly like accEcnOptionEnabled=false would, without
needing a second file) was run empirically during development and
produces a genuinely different number: marked=1000 (the
deliveredCePkts * snd_mss fallback estimate: 1 packet * the negotiated
1000-byte MSS -- not 988, since without the option there's no real
per-segment payload-length evidence, only the coarser packet count).
This 988-vs-1000 divergence is the concrete, numeric proof that the
byte-exact and packet-count-estimate code paths are actually different,
not just differently gated copies of the same number.

%inifile: omnetpp.ini
[General]
record-vector-results = false
ned-path = .;../../../../src;../../lib

network = inet.test.moduletest.lib.TcpTestNet1

cmdenv-event-banners=false
cmdenv-express-mode=false
cmdenv-log-prefix="[%c]: "

*.testing=false
*.tcptester.script="a3 ce;b2 delete;b3 delete;b4 delete;b5 delete"

*.cli_app.localAddress="10.0.0.1"
*.cli_app.localPort=1000
*.cli_app.connectAddress="10.0.0.2"
*.cli_app.connectPort=2000
*.cli_app.active=true
*.cli_app.tOpen=0s
*.cli_app.tSend=-1s
*.cli_app.sendBytes=0B
*.cli_app.tClose=-1s
*.cli_app.sendScript="0.5 5000; 1.0 100"

*.srv_app.localAddress="10.0.0.2"
*.srv_app.localPort=2000
*.srv_app.connectAddress="10.0.0.1"
*.srv_app.connectPort=1000
*.srv_app.active=false
*.srv_app.tOpen=0s
*.srv_app.tSend=-1s
*.srv_app.sendBytes=0B
*.srv_app.tClose=-1s
*.srv_app.sendScript=""

*.*_tcp.sackSupport = false
*.*_tcp.windowScalingSupport = false
*.*_tcp.timestampSupport = false
*.*_tcp.mss = 1000
*.*_tcp.delayedAcksEnabled = false
*.*_tcp.initialWindow = "rfc6928"

*.cli_tcp.tcpAlgorithmClass = "DcTcp"
*.srv_tcp.tcpAlgorithmClass = "TcpReno"

*.*_tcp.tcpEcnMode = "accecn"
*.*_tcp.accEcnOptionEnabled = true
*.*_tcp.accEcnOptionBeaconAcks = 1

# tcp-legacy.ini sets advertisedWindow=7504; OMNeT++ ini resolution takes the FIRST matching
# entry, so this override -- needed so the full 5000B burst fits in one window and all 5
# segments go out without waiting on an intermediate ACK -- must appear BEFORE the include.
*.*_tcp.advertisedWindow = 20000

include ../../lib/tcp-legacy.ini

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: postrun.pl
open FILE, '<test.out';
while($sor = <FILE>)
{
    if ($sor =~ /^\[testing\]: (.*)$/)
    {
        print "$1\n";
    }
}
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command:  perl ./postrun.pl
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# The one-ACK lag itself: at the burst-covering ACK (B006), byte-exact evidence hasn't
%# been folded in yet (this segment's own ACE block runs AFTER this call) -- expected, not a bug.
%# lens=bytes already, since the option arrived on the very first post-handshake ACK (A002).
%contains: stdout
DcTcp AccECN CE-byte accounting: lens=bytes marked=0 dctcp_bytesMarked=0
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# The actual G8.1 assertion, observed one ACK later (the follow-up send's ACK): marked=988,
%# the ONE CE-marked segment's real payload -- not ~4940 (5 segments), which RFC 8257's
%# boolean gotEce-gated approximation would have produced for this whole round.
%contains: stdout
DcTcp AccECN CE-byte accounting: lens=bytes marked=988 dctcp_bytesMarked=988
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
